According to a report of American Congress of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, half of the women who menstruate suffers from intense period pain. Mild pain is common during periods, but severe pain is not a good thing.Here are 7 things that you can do to ease the pain. But if you don t get relief despite trying some of these options, consult your doctor.A low-fat diet decreases overall inflammation in the body and also help with the period cramps. So start reducing fat from your daily diet. Add more vegetable to your regular diet plan. Try to get 25 to 35 percent of your daily calories from healthier fats found in fish, nuts, and vegetable oils.&nbsp;&nbsp;